
[1]purify

   PU'RIFY, v.t. [L. purifico; purus, pure, and facio, to make.]

   1. To make pure or clear; to free from extraneous admixture; as, to
   purify liquors or metals; to purify the blood; to purify the air.

   2. To free from pollution ceremonially; to remove whatever renders
   unclean and unfit for sacred services.

   Purify yourselves and your captives on the third day, and on the
   seventh day purify all your raiment. Num.31.

   3. To free from guilt or the defilement of sin; as, to purify the
   heart.

   Who gave himself for us, that he might redeem us from all iniquity, and
   purify to himself a peculiar people, zealous of good works. Tit.2.

   4. To clear form improprieties or barbarisms; as, to purify a language.

    PU'RIFY, v.i. To grow or become pure or clear. Liquors will gradually
                                   purify.
